Hi,

Does Junit4.0 Support Proxy like JunitX Does?

Here is the example from JUnitX, from their web site:



1.	Create a Production Source Class (which is the case a lot of times,
when Classes are written without implementing XP)



package junitx.demo;

class Inverter

{

  protected int _value = 0;



  public void flip ()

  {

    _value = 1 - _value;

  }

}



2.	Create a Test Class



package junitx.demo;

import junit.framework.*;

import junitx.framework.*;



public class TestInverter extends PrivateTestCase

{

  public TestInverter (String aName)

  {

    super (aName);

  }



  public void testInverter () throws TestAccessException

  {

    Object inverter = newInstance   (&quot;junitx.demo.Inverter&quot;, NOARGS);

    Object dummy    = invokeWithKey (inverter, &quot;flip&quot;, NOARGS);



    assertEquals (getInt (inverter, &quot;_value&quot;), 1);

  }

}



Notice: 

*	in this case the TestCase is not extended from &quot;TestCase&quot; as Junit
would have it.
*	getInt Method is from JUnitX API
*	JUnitX allows to create instances of any class the VM can access
using the newInstance method. Furthermore you can invoke any method of that
class independently of its access modifiers using the invokeWithKey method.
*	newInstance invokes a constructor of a tested class
*	invokeWithKey invokes a method on a proxied class using a method
key.



3.	Create a Test Proxy

package junitx.demo;

import java.lang.reflect.*;



import junit.framework.*;

import junitx.framework.*;



public class TestProxy extends junitx.framework.TestProxy

{

  public Object newInstance (Object[] anArgList)

  throws TestAccessException

  {

    try

    {

      return getProxiedClass ().getConstructor (anArgList).newInstance
(anArgList);

    }

    catch (Exception e)

    {

      throw new TestAccessException (&quot;could not instantiate &quot; +
getTestedClassName (), e);

    }

  }





  public Object newInstanceWithKey (String aConstructorKey, Object[]
anArgList)

  throws TestAccessException

  {

    try

    {

      return getProxiedClass ().getConstructor (aConstructorKey).newInstance
(anArgList);

    }

    catch (Exception e)

    {

      throw new TestAccessException (&quot;could not instantiate &quot; +
getTestedClassName (), e);

    }

  }

}

Note: 

*	TestProxy class allows JUnitX to locate test cases in different
packages than the tested classes. The code of the proxy is always the same



4.	Create a Test Package.



package junitx.demo;



import junit.framework.*;

import junitx.framework.*;



public class TestPackage implements junitx.framework.TestPackage

{

  static public Test suite ()

  {

    TestSuite suite = new TestSuite (&quot;Inverter tests&quot;);



    suite.addTestSuite (junitx.demo.TestInverter.class);



    return suite;

  }

}

So this DOES take one extra Step, and as far as JUnitX claims, this Extra
Step (STEP 3) needs to be done only once prepackage, and the code is always
the same (correct me if I am wrong)

Now with this framework, we have the ability to test protected methods,
other then that I don&#39;t see any real value (but I have no experience of
JUnitX, so I am not in a position to say that).

Anyone care to comment on this? In order to improve test cases.

